333 => 
array (
    'id' => 421,
    'article_id' => 70,
    'locale' => 'en',
    'title' => 'Risk hedging of bitcoin portfolio',
'body' => '<p>The dominant cryptocurrency has been on a downward path since it reached its annual high of $13900 at the end of June, and the bitcoin bulls have been in a difficult position. As price adjustments continue, traders have been looking for ways to hedge their long BTC positions. With the booming crypto derivatives market, participants can now better control their exposure with increasingly popular swap and futures contract products.<br /><br />BTC short term bearish<br /><br />Although the long-term bullish situation is still strong, a sustained short-term bearish sentiment can be seen in the K-line chart of the daily btc/usdt trading pair. In late June, btc/usdt trade pair broke through the price level of USD 13900 for the first time in more than a year. However, the trade pair failed to continue to break through the price level in mid July, thus forming resistance level, which is that the double top mode will be a downward trend. Recently, btc/usdt failed to stay above the double top neckline, which is about $10400, and more importantly, the RSI index of the daily chart is still below 50 and the MACD is still in a bearish range.<br /><br />Derivatives and Risk Management<br /><br />Given the recent price adjustment of BTC, the use of bitcoin derivatives to manage risk is now a topic everyone wants to revisit. If it is an investor in traditional financial markets, it should not be unfamiliar with derivatives trading.<br /><br />In textbooks, derivative is a kind of financial securities whose value is determined by its related assets. This is a contract involving two or more parties, and the related assets can be stocks, bonds, commodities, currencies, interest rates or market indices.<br /><br />Why are derivatives so popular? Because it can be used to hedge positions, speculate about directional changes in related assets, or leverage holdings. In terms of risk management, it is also a multi-functional tool. As part of the risk dispersion strategy, many financial institutions keep trading derivatives such as swaps and forward.<br /><br />Derivatives in the field of digital currency<br /><br />Compared with traditional derivatives market, the contract market of digital currency is relatively new and smaller, but this does not mean that the digital currency market is not unprofitable. Similar to stock futures or interest rate swaps, BTC derivatives can avoid fluctuations in the digital currency market and price changes, and can be used as hedging instruments to offset potential losses.<br /><br />Most importantly, traders can use contracts to speculate on the price of leveraged digital currencies, thereby maximizing potential profits. There are three main contract products in the digital currency world: 1) perpetual contract（ 2) Futures contracts（ 3) Option contracts.<br /><br />Hedging<br /><br />Although BTC\'s downside risk is increasing and may eventually create buying opportunities for BTC bulls, BTC\'s negative mood has increased, and for risk management, investors are advised to review their hedging and arbitrage strategies. Hedging involves the use of multiple concurrent bets in the opposite direction in order to limit the risk of serious investment losses. First, let\'s look back at the differences between hedging strategies.<br /><br />Let\'s take delivery contracts as an example of hedging.<br /><br />There are other factors that affect overall hedging strategies, such as the closing date, the decision to make a long or short run, and the number of contracts.<br /><br />Protect multiple positions<br /><br />Sustainability is another structural tool that investors can use. We assume that the spot market price is $9500, while the transaction price of BTC is $9600. Investors can open short positions of the same value ($9500) in the spot market at $9500 and at the same time in the sustainability contract market.<br /><br />1. when the price of BTC increases, investors can profit from the spot market.<br /><br />2. when the price of BTC falls, investors can close short positions of the perpetual contract and profit from them to make up for the losses in the spot market.<br /><br />However, if long-term holding contracts are part of their strategy, traders should also consider financing and settlement factors.<br /><br />arbitrage opportunity<br /><br />Arbitrage is to profit from unbalanced markets, trading the same commodity spread between multiple markets, which involves the purchase and sale of goods in a short period of time. We assume that bitcoin trading price in spot market is $9500, while BTC\'s perpetual contract price is $9600. Investors buy bitcoin in the spot market for $9500 and open short positions of the same value ($9600) in the sustainability contract at the same time.<br /><br />1. if the interest margin between the two is reduced, investors can make profits.<br /><br />2. if the difference increases, the unrealized profit and loss of the transaction will become negative. In this case, investors can wait for the settlement to expire. The marked price of a contract is usually calculated based on spot price, so the tag price is very close to the spot price, and the profit is about 9600-9500 USD = 100 USD<br /><br />3. when the spot price is higher than the contract price, the total profit is more than 100 USD.<br /><br />conclusion<br /><br />Hedging is not the pursuit of risk-free transactions. Instead, it is an attempt to reduce known risks when trading. This is an important strategy in traditional financial market and business management. Digital currency traders can adopt the method widely used in stock, foreign exchange and commodity trading. Much like any other risk / return transaction, hedging can lead to a reduction in the return of the parties concerned, but it can provide important downside risk protection.</p>',
    'excerpt' => NULL,
),
334 => 
array (
    'id' => 422,
    'article_id' => 69,
    'locale' => 'en',
    'title' => 'Bitcoin Arbitrage Strategy Report',
'body' => '<p>We previously published a report on the relationship between spot leverage rates and perpetual contract capital rates to find arbitrage opportunities, which showed a return on investment of 1.66 per cent in seven days. However, this is best done on a one-stop service exchange such as okex, which provides both delivery / Sustainability contracts and spot trading, which will exempt the money miner fee and the time of the chain transfer.<br /><br />In this article, we will introduce a more traditional, cash arbitrage that can also be used on okex.<br /><br />What is the cash arbitrage strategy<br /><br />The price of goods reflects the confidence of investors in the market in particular targets. Whenever the market fluctuates, spot price and futures price will be very different (base difference), the more obvious the price difference is, the more favorable arbitrage.<br /><br />Under normal circumstances, quarterly contracts have a larger base difference than that of weekly contracts and two week contracts. Because the longer the contract expires, the more uncertain factors are, we will take quarterly contracts as an example in this article.<br /><br />If we look at the graph, we can see that the highest base difference is 581.7 on July 10, then dropped to -121.64 on July 17 and bounced back to the 100-200 range.<br /><br />By drawing the base spread over time (per hour), we can know that the base difference of this contract fluctuates between 100-200 for most of July.<br /><br />Practice<br /><br />Buy BTC of 1000usdt in spot market, transfer it to delivery contract account and open ten quarterly contracts, with value equal to 1000 USD, and all positions remain delta neutral (delta value of held position portfolio is 0, that is, price change of BTC will not affect final income).<br /><br />If you only have BTC in your account, you can leverage usdt and repeat the above process. However, because of the need to take leverage interest, your income will be lower in the end.<br /><br />Case 1:<br /><br />Taking 1000 usdt as the starting capital, the current arbitrage strategy was adopted at 11:00 a.m. on July 10. The position was closed and the income was calculated when the 0:00 basis difference on July 17 was negative<br /><br />Case 2:<br /><br />Taking 0.1btc as the initial capital, the company borrowed 1000usdt with leverage and adopted the current arbitrage strategy. It opened at 11:00 a.m. on July 10, and closed the position at 0:00 on July 17 when the base difference was negative and calculated the income:<br /><br />Basis<br /><br />If the base spread keeps rising and does not decline, the portfolio may have temporary losses, but the closer the maturity of the contract, the base difference will gradually close to 0.<br /><br />wave<br /><br />If your position is heavy, it will take a certain time to be digested by the market when closing positions, and your cost will be affected by the change of base difference during closing.<br /><br />Usdt price<br /><br />The dollar price of usdt is too hard to mention, and the opening of spot market is equivalent to selling usdt for us dollars.<br /><br />Strong risk<br /><br />If usdt is used as the starting capital, there is no strong risk of leveling, but traders using leveraged borrowing currency may increase margin once and again due to market fluctuation to avoid the opening of positions.<br /><br />optimization<br /><br />The base differences should be analyzed more finely, and the granularity of the sampling interval can be refined to the minute level rather than the hour level.<br /><br />The market is analyzed by using the transaction big data on okex to better find the operating points of opening and closing positions and thus make profits. For example, the negative basis difference happened twice in July. We can consider opening at the negative basis difference and closing when the base difference is positive.<br /><br />Before the delivery, the return of BTC cannot be transferred to the spot account. In order to avoid the risk of fluctuation of BTC price, we can hold contract position or leverage position to offset the risk.</p>',
    'excerpt' => NULL,
),
335 => 
array (
    'id' => 423,
    'article_id' => 68,
    'locale' => 'en',
    'title' => 'Technical indicators of bitcoin digital assets',
'body' => '<p>Whether stock investors or investors, technical analysis is a very important part in trading. The study of historical price trends and other trading related data can help us find trading opportunities and predict the direction of price changes. Technical analysis is widely used in stock, futures, commodity trading, foreign exchange and other asset classes. In the era of digital currency, traders are trying to develop some analysis tools that are more in line with the rapid growth of assets. At the same time, they bring the traditional financial way of technical analysis to the field of digital assets.<br /><br />Bollinger Bands<br /><br />Brin belt is the most widely used indicator in trading, named after John Bollinger, an American asset management manager and technical analyst. The range of the brin belt is represented by a set of positive and negative lines describing the standard deviation based on the price moving average (usually 20-sma). Because the standard deviation is the observation index of volatility, when the market price fluctuates violently, the Bollinger belt is relatively wider, which is usually considered as the signal of exit. When the volatility is small, the Bollinger belt shrinks, which may be the potential signal of intensified volatility, which is generally regarded as the signal of entrance. There are also many traders who think that when the price approaches the upper line of the brin belt, it means that the market is overbought. On the contrary, when the price approaches the lower line of the brin belt, it means that the market is overbought.</p>',
    'excerpt' => NULL,
),
